Task 1: Git Installation and Configuration
Subtask 1.1: Verify Git Installation
First, let's check if Git is installed and view its version:

git --version
You should see output similar to:

git version 2.34.1
Subtask 1.2: Configure Git User Information
Before using Git, we need to set up your identity. This information will be associated with your commits:

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"
Replace "Your Name" and "your.email@example.com" with your actual information.

Subtask 1.3: Verify Configuration
Check that your configuration was set correctly:

git config --list
Look for your name and email in the output.

Task 2: Initialize Repository and Basic Operations
Subtask 2.1: Create Project Directory and Initialize Repository
Let's create a new project directory and initialize it as a Git repository:

mkdir my-first-repo
cd my-first-repo
git init
You should see output like:

Initialized empty Git repository in /home/user/my-first-repo/.git/
Subtask 2.2: Check Repository Status
View the current status of your repository:

git status
This shows you're on the main branch with no commits yet.

Subtask 2.3: Create Your First File
Create a simple text file to track:

echo "# My First Git Project" > README.md
echo "This is a sample project to learn Git basics." >> README.md
Let's also create a simple Python script:

cat > hello.py << 'EOF'
#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
A simple hello world program
"""

def main():
    print("Hello, Git World!")
    print("This is my first versioned program.")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
EOF
Subtask 2.4: Check Status After Adding Files
git status
Notice that Git detects the new files but they are "untracked."

Task 3: Staging and Committing Changes
Subtask 3.1: Stage Files for Commit
Add files to the staging area:

git add README.md
git add hello.py
Alternatively, you can add all files at once:

git add .
Subtask 3.2: Check Status After Staging
git status
The files should now appear as "Changes to be committed."

Subtask 3.3: Make Your First Commit
Commit the staged changes with a descriptive message:

git commit -m "Initial commit: Add README and hello world program"
Subtask 3.4: View Commit History
git log
This shows your commit with details like author, date, and message.

For a more compact view:

git log --oneline
Task 4: Making Additional Changes and Commits
Subtask 4.1: Modify Existing Files
Let's update our Python program:

cat >> hello.py << 'EOF'

def greet_user(name):
    """Greet a specific user"""
    print(f"Hello, {name}! Welcome to Git!")

# Add a new greeting
greet_user("Student")
EOF
Subtask 4.2: Create a New File
cat > config.txt << 'EOF'
# Configuration file for my project
version=1.0
author=Student
description=Learning Git basics
EOF
Subtask 4.3: Check What Changed
git status
git diff hello.py
The git diff command shows exactly what changed in the file.

Subtask 4.4: Stage and Commit Changes
git add hello.py config.txt
git commit -m "Add user greeting function and configuration file"
Subtask 4.5: View Updated History
git log --oneline
You should now see two commits in your history.

Task 5: Working with Branches
Subtask 5.1: Create a New Branch
Branches allow you to work on different features without affecting the main code:

git branch feature-improvements
git checkout feature-improvements
Or create and switch in one command:

git checkout -b feature-improvements
Note: If the branch already exists from the previous command, use:

git checkout feature-improvements
Subtask 5.2: Verify Current Branch
git branch
The asterisk (*) shows your current branch.

Subtask 5.3: Make Changes in the New Branch
Let's add a new feature to our Python program:

cat >> hello.py << 'EOF'

def display_info():
    """Display project information"""
    print("=" * 30)
    print("Project: My First Git Project")
    print("Version: 1.0")
    print("Learning: Git version control")
    print("=" * 30)

# Display project info
display_info()
EOF
Subtask 5.4: Commit Changes in Feature Branch
git add hello.py
git commit -m "Add project information display function"
Subtask 5.5: View Branch History
git log --oneline
Notice this branch has the new commit that doesn't exist in main.

Task 6: Merging Branches
Subtask 6.1: Switch Back to Main Branch
git checkout main
Subtask 6.2: Check Main Branch Content
cat hello.py
Notice that the changes from the feature branch are not here.

Subtask 6.3: Merge Feature Branch
git merge feature-improvements
Git will automatically merge the changes if there are no conflicts.

Subtask 6.4: Verify Merge
cat hello.py
git log --oneline
The main branch now contains all the changes from the feature branch.

Subtask 6.5: Clean Up Merged Branch
Since the feature is now merged, we can delete the feature branch:

git branch -d feature-improvements
Task 7: Cloning and Working with Repository Copies
Subtask 7.1: Create a Bare Repository (Simulating Remote)
To demonstrate cloning, let's create a bare repository that simulates a remote repository:

cd ..
git clone --bare my-first-repo my-first-repo.git
Subtask 7.2: Clone the Repository
Now let's clone this repository to create a new working copy:

git clone my-first-repo.git cloned-repo
cd cloned-repo
Subtask 7.3: Verify Cloned Content
ls -la
cat README.md
cat hello.py
git log --oneline
The cloned repository contains all the history and files from the original.

Subtask 7.4: Make Changes in Cloned Repository
echo "## Installation Instructions" >> README.md
echo "1. Clone this repository" >> README.md
echo "2. Run: python3 hello.py" >> README.md
Subtask 7.5: Commit and Push Changes
git add README.md
git commit -m "Add installation instructions to README"
git push origin main
Task 8: Advanced Git Operations
Subtask 8.1: View Detailed Commit Information
git show
This shows the details of the most recent commit.

Subtask 8.2: Check File History
git log --follow README.md
This shows all commits that modified the README.md file.

Subtask 8.3: Create and Work with Tags
Tags are useful for marking specific versions:

git tag -a v1.0 -m "First stable version"
git tag
Subtask 8.4: View Repository Statistics
git log --stat
This shows which files were changed in each commit.

Task 9: Handling Common Scenarios
Subtask 9.1: Checking Out Previous Commits
git log --oneline
Copy the hash of your first commit, then:

git checkout <first-commit-hash>
cat hello.py
Notice how the file looks like it did in the first commit.

Subtask 9.2: Return to Latest Version
git checkout main
cat hello.py
You're back to the latest version.

Subtask 9.3: Create a New Branch from Current State
git checkout -b documentation-update
echo "# Documentation" > DOCS.md
echo "This project demonstrates basic Git operations." >> DOCS.md
git add DOCS.md
git commit -m "Add documentation file"
Subtask 9.4: Switch Between Branches
git checkout main
ls
git checkout documentation-update
ls
Notice how the DOCS.md file appears and disappears based on the branch.

Task 10: Repository Maintenance and Best Practices
Subtask 10.1: View Repository Size and Objects
git count-objects -v
Subtask 10.2: Create .gitignore File
git checkout main
cat > .gitignore << 'EOF'
# Python cache files
__pycache__/
*.pyc
*.pyo

# Log files
*.log

# Temporary files
*.tmp
*~

# IDE files
.vscode/
.idea/
EOF
Subtask 10.3: Test .gitignore
echo "temporary data" > temp.tmp
echo "print('test')" > test.pyc
git status
Notice that Git ignores the files matching patterns in .gitignore.

Subtask 10.4: Commit .gitignore
git add .gitignore
git commit -m "Add .gitignore file to exclude temporary files"
Troubleshooting Common Issues
Issue 1: Merge Conflicts
If you encounter merge conflicts, Git will mark the conflicting areas in files. Edit the files to resolve conflicts, then:

git add <resolved-file>
git commit -m "Resolve merge conflict"
Issue 2: Accidentally Committed Wrong Files
To unstage files before committing:

git reset HEAD <filename>
Issue 3: Want to Undo Last Commit
To undo the last commit but keep changes:

git reset --soft HEAD~1
Issue 4: Check What Will Be Committed
Before committing, always check:

git diff --staged
